00:03:03.778 --> 00:03:04.750
AUDIENCE: Wolverine?

00:03:04.750 --> 00:03:06.136
NEIL GIBSON: Absolutely, yeah.

00:03:06.136 --> 00:03:08.260
I had just finished university
and was backpacking,

00:03:08.260 --> 00:03:10.750
and I was in Vancouver at the
time, and the film "X-Men"

00:03:10.750 --> 00:03:12.400
had just come out.

00:03:12.400 --> 00:03:13.540
And I had a friend of mine.

00:03:13.540 --> 00:03:15.498
We used to joke that he
wanted to be Wolverine,

00:03:15.498 --> 00:03:18.010
so I thought I'd buy
that as a joke present.

00:03:18.010 --> 00:03:20.620
I went into the shop,
and at that time--

00:03:20.620 --> 00:03:24.219
this was back in 2000, all the
top creators, writers of comics

00:03:24.219 --> 00:03:24.760
were British.

00:03:24.760 --> 00:03:28.210
You had Alan Moore, Neil Gaiman,
Garth Ennis, Warren Ellis,

00:03:28.210 --> 00:03:29.522
Grant Morrison.

00:03:29.522 --> 00:03:31.480
And when I got talking
to the guys in the shop,

00:03:31.480 --> 00:03:34.480
and they assumed I
personally knew these people,

00:03:34.480 --> 00:03:37.130
and I had to point out I
hadn't even heard of them.

00:03:37.130 --> 00:03:39.130
And then it goes to a
blank look, and they said,

00:03:39.130 --> 00:03:41.664
"but you've read
'Watchmen,' right?"

00:03:41.664 --> 00:03:43.090
Well, I said, "No."

00:03:43.090 --> 00:03:44.389
They said, "Stay here."

00:03:44.389 --> 00:03:46.180
And this girl went to
the back of the shop.

00:03:46.180 --> 00:03:47.971
And I'll never forget
the way she did this.

00:03:47.971 --> 00:03:51.520
She came back and with such
intensity said, "Buy this."

00:03:54.630 --> 00:03:55.220
And I did.

00:03:55.220 --> 00:03:57.470
And I remember feeling silly
as I walked out the shop.

00:03:57.470 --> 00:04:00.940
I thought, "I spent $30 on
something I don't really want."

00:04:00.940 --> 00:04:04.270
But I read it, and it
changed my life, really.

00:04:04.270 --> 00:04:07.460
I became a massive fan of
comics for the next 12 years.

00:04:07.460 --> 00:04:09.227
I read loads of them.

00:04:09.227 --> 00:04:10.810
And the reason it
changed my life is I

00:04:10.810 --> 00:04:13.900
didn't realize how
intelligent comics could be.

00:04:13.900 --> 00:04:16.390
I assumed it was all just
people punching each other

00:04:16.390 --> 00:04:20.450
or the "Beano," like kid stuff.

00:04:20.450 --> 00:04:22.690
So why did it affect me so much?

00:04:22.690 --> 00:04:25.030
I had preconceptions,
and a lot of people

00:04:25.030 --> 00:04:28.270
do about comics who
don't read them.

00:04:28.270 --> 00:04:30.630
So let's talk about
the first point,

00:04:30.630 --> 00:04:32.661
public perception of comics.

00:04:32.661 --> 00:04:35.160
And first of all, the difference
between medium and content.

00:04:35.160 --> 00:04:38.346
So who here used to
listen to music as a kid?

00:04:38.346 --> 00:04:39.879
See, you guys are awesome.

00:04:39.879 --> 00:04:42.170
Normally, I do this talk,
and no one raises their hand.

00:04:42.170 --> 00:04:43.820
So I make a joke saying
you're all liars or something.

00:04:43.820 --> 00:04:45.930
But you guys are actually
very interactive.

00:04:45.930 --> 00:04:47.380
I even have bribes here.

00:04:47.380 --> 00:04:50.430
I threw sweets to people,
the first hand that goes up.

00:04:50.430 --> 00:04:52.020
You guys just all raised them.

00:04:52.020 --> 00:04:55.050
So you don't get the sweets.

00:04:55.050 --> 00:04:57.810
So the answer is everyone
listened to music as a kid.

00:04:57.810 --> 00:05:00.030
And I'm not saying I own that.

00:05:00.030 --> 00:05:02.362
I'm not saying I owned that.

00:05:02.362 --> 00:05:04.380
I did.

00:05:04.380 --> 00:05:07.050
But your tastes change
as you get older,

00:05:07.050 --> 00:05:09.840
and normally the content
you consume would change.

00:05:09.840 --> 00:05:11.590
It's the same with TV.

00:05:11.590 --> 00:05:13.830
Like, I watched "Sesame
Street" as a kid.

00:05:13.830 --> 00:05:15.450
I don't anymore.

00:05:15.450 --> 00:05:18.530
Your tastes change, but the
medium is still the same.

00:05:18.530 --> 00:05:20.580
You still consume
the same medium.

00:05:20.580 --> 00:05:23.485
But for comics, well, you
could read it as a kid,

00:05:23.485 --> 00:05:25.830
and especially in this
country, it's the "Beano."

00:05:25.830 --> 00:05:28.010
And a lot of them just stop.

00:05:28.010 --> 00:05:30.845
But they don't need to, because
the content is out there

00:05:30.845 --> 00:05:33.250
for people, but more
people just don't find it,

00:05:33.250 --> 00:05:36.500
because they see it is
just a limited palette.

00:05:36.500 --> 00:05:40.440
A lot of people I recommend
"Sandman" to, for example.

00:05:40.440 --> 00:05:41.340
Why do they stop?

00:05:41.340 --> 00:05:43.215
Well, a lot of it is
public pressure as well.

00:05:43.215 --> 00:05:44.910
I remember when I
first told a friend

00:05:44.910 --> 00:05:48.530
of mine reading a manga comic
called "Lone Wolf and Cub."

00:05:48.530 --> 00:05:50.310
And I was waiting for
her in a restaurant.

00:05:50.310 --> 00:05:53.710
And she said, "You can't read
comics forever, can you?"

00:05:53.710 --> 00:05:56.270
And it was a little
bit offensive to me

00:05:56.270 --> 00:05:58.530
because she just genuinely
looked down on them.

00:05:58.530 --> 00:06:01.590
And so why is it that
people do look down on them?

00:06:01.590 --> 00:06:05.580
Well, I apologize to any
Rob Liefeld fans out there,

00:06:05.580 --> 00:06:08.490
but I don't blame people for
it if the available content is

00:06:08.490 --> 00:06:09.045
awful.

00:06:09.045 --> 00:06:11.370
If you're new to comics
and you go into a shop,

00:06:11.370 --> 00:06:13.245
or you're trying to
graduate from the "Beano"

00:06:13.245 --> 00:06:16.580
and this is what you discover
in the shop, well, I'm sorry.

00:06:16.580 --> 00:06:18.210
That's just silly.

00:06:18.210 --> 00:06:19.850
I mean look at the
proportions here.

00:06:19.850 --> 00:06:21.790
No human looks like that.

00:06:21.790 --> 00:06:22.810
It's overly muscly.

00:06:22.810 --> 00:06:24.740
The anatomy is completely wrong.

00:06:24.740 --> 00:06:28.190
And however bad male characters
are portrayed in comics,

00:06:28.190 --> 00:06:30.920
female characters
are usually worse.

00:06:30.920 --> 00:06:32.540
That is a human spine.

00:06:32.540 --> 00:06:34.130
It's right angles.

00:06:34.130 --> 00:06:35.910
It's ridiculous!

00:06:35.910 --> 00:06:37.451
So if that's what people--

00:06:37.451 --> 00:06:39.950
if that's all they see when
they first go into a comic shop,

00:06:39.950 --> 00:06:42.740
I don't blame them
for not trying more.

00:06:42.740 --> 00:06:45.244
Another reason is,
historically, it was humorous.

00:06:45.244 --> 00:06:47.410
Comics were called comics
because they were comical.

00:06:47.410 --> 00:06:50.442
Another word for them
is the funny pages.

00:06:50.442 --> 00:06:52.400
And my book there, that
psychological thriller,

00:06:52.400 --> 00:06:55.700
"Twisted Dark," I gave it to my
uncle, and he read a bit of it

00:06:55.700 --> 00:07:00.500
and said, "Neil, is this
supposed to make me laugh?"

00:07:00.500 --> 00:07:02.490
No, it's not, but
people just assume

00:07:02.490 --> 00:07:06.920
that comics should be funny.

00:07:06.920 --> 00:07:09.720
Another reason they're looked
down upon is poor logic.

00:07:09.720 --> 00:07:13.970
So if someone says "all
crows are black," fine.

00:07:13.970 --> 00:07:17.224
Oh, this bird is black,
therefore, it must be a crow.

00:07:17.224 --> 00:07:18.890
That's not really
good logic, but people

00:07:18.890 --> 00:07:20.729
do apply it to comics.

00:07:20.729 --> 00:07:22.520
All children's books
tend to have pictures,

00:07:22.520 --> 00:07:23.480
because that's how
they learn what

00:07:23.480 --> 00:07:25.460
the world is like, what
a castle looks like,

00:07:25.460 --> 00:07:26.877
what a rocket looks like.

00:07:26.877 --> 00:07:28.460
So all children's
books have pictures.

00:07:28.460 --> 00:07:29.940
Oh, this book has pictures.

00:07:29.940 --> 00:07:31.860
Therefore it must be
a children's book.

00:07:31.860 --> 00:07:33.600
Now, you guys are
all Google employees

00:07:33.600 --> 00:07:35.058
who are super smart,
so you'd never

00:07:35.058 --> 00:07:38.360
make that kind of mistake,
but a lot of people do.

00:07:38.360 --> 00:07:40.960
But I think the main reason in
the English-speaking language

00:07:40.960 --> 00:07:42.501
that it's looked
down upon is because

00:07:42.501 --> 00:07:43.890
of this guy, Fredric Wertham.

00:07:43.890 --> 00:07:46.170
Does anyone here
know who this is?

00:07:46.170 --> 00:07:47.190
No.

00:07:47.190 --> 00:07:49.717
He wrote a book called
"Seduction of the Innocent,"

00:07:49.717 --> 00:07:51.300
in which he wrote
that comic books are

00:07:51.300 --> 00:07:53.730
dangerous to children.

00:07:53.730 --> 00:07:56.722
And he proved that
children reading comics

00:07:56.722 --> 00:07:58.680
were more likely to be
anti-social, more likely

00:07:58.680 --> 00:08:02.790
to drink alcohol, to take
drugs, and commit crime.

00:08:02.790 --> 00:08:06.180
He was so powerful that
Congress launched an inquiry

00:08:06.180 --> 00:08:07.200
into comics.

00:08:07.200 --> 00:08:10.200
Across schools in America,
they burned comic books.

00:08:10.200 --> 00:08:11.571
it's true.

00:08:11.571 --> 00:08:14.070
And what Congress did was they
launched the Comic Book Code,

00:08:14.070 --> 00:08:16.486
which meant that comic books
could not be marketed or have

00:08:16.486 --> 00:08:17.840
adult or mature themes.

00:08:17.840 --> 00:08:19.920
Had to be limited to
people 13 or younger.

00:08:19.920 --> 00:08:22.200
So it made the material puerile.

00:08:22.200 --> 00:08:24.510
So unlike content
in France or Japan,

00:08:24.510 --> 00:08:26.280
where it can have
whatever you want,

00:08:26.280 --> 00:08:30.480
until fairly recently, it
had to be limited age-wise.

00:08:30.480 --> 00:08:31.890
And when he died--

00:08:31.890 --> 00:08:33.510
in his book, he went
on to say that "I

00:08:33.510 --> 00:08:35.760
think Hitler was a beginner
compared to the comic book

00:08:35.760 --> 00:08:36.566
industry."

00:08:36.566 --> 00:08:38.190
That's an incredible
statement to make.

00:08:38.190 --> 00:08:40.850
That shows you how
anti-comics he was.

00:08:40.850 --> 00:08:43.020
And when he died, it was
proved that he fabricated

00:08:43.020 --> 00:08:45.140
everything, made it all up.

00:08:45.140 --> 00:08:46.890
But we're still feeling
the effects today.

00:08:46.890 --> 00:08:50.700
The good news is that
perceptions do change.

00:08:50.700 --> 00:08:53.450
Does anyone know
who this guy is?

00:08:53.450 --> 00:08:54.100
No?

00:08:54.100 --> 00:08:56.610
OK, well, this is Jack LaLanne.

00:08:56.610 --> 00:08:58.380
You see those handcuffs there?

00:08:58.380 --> 00:09:04.230
He swam a mile upriver, towing
70 rowboats behind his back.

00:09:04.230 --> 00:09:06.810
A mile with 70 rowboats, the
last one full of passengers.

00:09:06.810 --> 00:09:09.570
And he did it with his hands
handcuffed behind his back.

00:09:09.570 --> 00:09:12.020
And he did it when
he was 70 years old.

00:09:12.020 --> 00:09:14.556
One rowboat per
year for his life.

00:09:14.556 --> 00:09:15.930
And the reason I
mention all this

00:09:15.930 --> 00:09:18.210
is because he is the guy who
invented weights machines.

00:09:18.210 --> 00:09:20.376
Gyms as they exist today
wouldn't exist without him.

00:09:20.376 --> 00:09:22.140
He was a hero of
Arnold Schwarzenegger.

00:09:22.140 --> 00:09:24.870
And when he first started
saying that you should lift out

00:09:24.870 --> 00:09:27.720
with weights and use these
machines, doctors at the time

00:09:27.720 --> 00:09:30.630
said, working out with weights
will give people heart attacks

00:09:30.630 --> 00:09:32.460
and they will lose
their sex drive.

00:09:32.460 --> 00:09:34.281
They were vehemently
opposed to him.

00:09:34.281 --> 00:09:36.030
But obviously, today,
things have changed.

00:09:36.030 --> 00:09:38.825
Now it's a central part
of any athletic training.

00:09:38.825 --> 00:09:40.200
Another perception
that's changed

00:09:40.200 --> 00:09:43.500
is "Smoking is good for you."

00:09:43.500 --> 00:09:47.340
More doctors smoked Camels
than any other cigarette.

00:09:47.340 --> 00:09:48.990
And that is a young
Ronald Reagan,

00:09:48.990 --> 00:09:53.660
the future president of
America, advertising cigarettes.

00:09:53.660 --> 00:09:55.555
Now, that wouldn't happen today.

00:09:55.555 --> 00:09:57.930
Another thing that's changed,
"Women have smaller brains.

00:09:57.930 --> 00:09:59.524
They aren't as
intelligent as men."

00:09:59.524 --> 00:10:01.440
This was a real reason
why women weren't given

00:10:01.440 --> 00:10:03.776
the vote, a real reason quoted.

00:10:03.776 --> 00:10:05.400
Now, it is true that,
physically, women

00:10:05.400 --> 00:10:07.066
do have smaller brains,
but intelligence

00:10:07.066 --> 00:10:08.080
is made of gray matter.

00:10:08.080 --> 00:10:09.220
Women have a higher
percentage of that,

00:10:09.220 --> 00:10:10.261
so it works out the same.

00:10:12.500 --> 00:10:13.402
And finally this--

00:10:13.402 --> 00:10:15.610
"No black man will ever be
considered for president."

00:10:15.610 --> 00:10:18.390
This was said by the
Reverend Jeremiah Wright

00:10:18.390 --> 00:10:21.365
three years before
Barack Obama was elected.

00:10:21.365 --> 00:10:24.780
And what I find amazing
is that this reverend

00:10:24.780 --> 00:10:25.890
was his own reverend.

00:10:29.012 --> 00:10:30.720
Anyway, the good news
is that perceptions

00:10:30.720 --> 00:10:33.550
do change, and the perceptions
of comics will change,

00:10:33.550 --> 00:10:36.010
and with your help,
will happen sooner.

00:10:36.010 --> 00:10:38.460
That's the perception of
comics, but what advantage

00:10:38.460 --> 00:10:40.380
do they have over other mediums?

00:10:40.380 --> 00:10:41.820
Well, let's start with pacing.

00:10:44.660 --> 00:10:47.870
For me, comics sit in
between books and film.

00:10:47.870 --> 00:10:50.780
The best communication you ever
get, I think, in my experience,

00:10:50.780 --> 00:10:53.030
is when you're with someone
you're in complete rapport

00:10:53.030 --> 00:10:53.540
with.

00:10:53.540 --> 00:10:55.420
You finish each other's
sentences, the way they speak,

00:10:55.420 --> 00:10:57.410
their cadence, their
intonation, the way they move,

00:10:57.410 --> 00:10:59.451
you're just completely in
sync and you understand

00:10:59.451 --> 00:11:00.570
what they're saying 100%.

00:11:00.570 --> 00:11:02.216
But that's very
rare, and you tend

00:11:02.216 --> 00:11:03.590
to be very similar
to that person

00:11:03.590 --> 00:11:05.600
to be able to get
that kind of rapport.

00:11:05.600 --> 00:11:07.430
So you don't have
that mass appeal.

00:11:07.430 --> 00:11:11.571
But with books, the advantage
of books is you decide the pace.

00:11:11.571 --> 00:11:13.320
You can go as fast or
as slow as you like.

00:11:13.320 --> 00:11:14.736
You can skip
passages if you want.

00:11:14.736 --> 00:11:15.620
You can skim read.

00:11:15.620 --> 00:11:18.120
Or you can pore over what the
meanings of these actual words

00:11:18.120 --> 00:11:19.130
are.

00:11:19.130 --> 00:11:21.020
With films, the director
decides the pace.

00:11:21.020 --> 00:11:22.700
You don't get a
choice in the matter.

00:11:22.700 --> 00:11:25.610
And that lands you into trouble
sometimes, because, for myself,

00:11:25.610 --> 00:11:28.580
for example, I sometimes
speak too quickly for people.

00:11:28.580 --> 00:11:30.470
What's worse is people
who speak too slowly.

00:11:30.470 --> 00:11:32.276
That just drives me mad.

00:11:32.276 --> 00:11:34.150
You don't get a choice
when it gets to films.

00:11:34.150 --> 00:11:38.420
It's given to you at the
speed the director chooses.

00:11:38.420 --> 00:11:41.687
And sometimes it's too much,
sometimes it's too slow.

00:11:41.687 --> 00:11:43.520
Comics, to me, is
wonderfully in the middle,

00:11:43.520 --> 00:11:46.010
because, again, like
books, you decide the pace,

00:11:46.010 --> 00:11:47.711
but you can be guided
by the pictures.

00:11:47.711 --> 00:11:49.460
And it's very efficient,
because a picture

00:11:49.460 --> 00:11:50.772
says a thousand words.

00:11:50.772 --> 00:11:52.730
They can reduce the amount
of text in the page,

00:11:52.730 --> 00:11:56.080
or the size of the panels,
or the detail of the panels

00:11:56.080 --> 00:11:57.080
to guide you through it.

00:11:59.700 --> 00:12:03.209
With books, you create the
entire character's surroundings

00:12:03.209 --> 00:12:03.750
in the world.

00:12:03.750 --> 00:12:06.090
If you want to lose yourself
for a couple of hours,

00:12:06.090 --> 00:12:09.180
a great way to do that is to
play video games, to program,

00:12:09.180 --> 00:12:12.030
or to read a book.

00:12:12.030 --> 00:12:14.275
With a film, you see and
hear all the characters

00:12:14.275 --> 00:12:16.950
but are limited
by the direction.

00:12:16.950 --> 00:12:20.160
And again, with comics, you
get to see the body language

00:12:20.160 --> 00:12:23.700
of someone, what someone's
feeling in their body in how

00:12:23.700 --> 00:12:24.900
they move and how they--

00:12:24.900 --> 00:12:27.409
but the transition
between the panels

00:12:27.409 --> 00:12:29.700
and how the characters sound,
what they're really like,

00:12:29.700 --> 00:12:32.910
is, again, in your head.

00:12:32.910 --> 00:12:34.940
All of these, your
interpretation

00:12:34.940 --> 00:12:38.950
can be very personal, because
they're all great mediums.

00:12:38.950 --> 00:12:40.999
But another way of saying
this is that no medium

00:12:40.999 --> 00:12:42.040
is superior to the other.

00:12:42.040 --> 00:12:44.757
They all have their own
advantages and disadvantages.

00:12:44.757 --> 00:12:46.590
For me, one of the main
advantages of comics

00:12:46.590 --> 00:12:47.173
is the pacing.

00:12:51.030 --> 00:12:54.640
Next is ease of vision.

00:12:54.640 --> 00:12:56.860
I've got a question
for you guys.

00:12:56.860 --> 00:12:59.830
First right question
gets a packet of sweets.

00:12:59.830 --> 00:13:02.000
So what percentage of
neurons in the brain cortex

00:13:02.000 --> 00:13:04.490
do you think is
devoted to hearing?

00:13:04.490 --> 00:13:05.200
AUDIENCE: 20%.

00:13:05.200 --> 00:13:07.386
NEIL GIBSON: 20%.

00:13:07.386 --> 00:13:08.841
Anyone else?

00:13:08.841 --> 00:13:09.382
AUDIENCE: 10.

00:13:09.382 --> 00:13:10.879
NEIL GIBSON: 10?

00:13:10.879 --> 00:13:12.380
One more.

00:13:12.380 --> 00:13:13.090
5?

00:13:13.090 --> 00:13:14.700
We're getting closer.

00:13:14.700 --> 00:13:16.990
It's only 3%.

00:13:16.990 --> 00:13:19.950
What about touch?

00:13:19.950 --> 00:13:20.800
AUDIENCE: 5%.

00:13:20.800 --> 00:13:22.029
NEIL GIBSON: 5%?

00:13:22.029 --> 00:13:22.570
AUDIENCE: 1%.

00:13:22.570 --> 00:13:23.810
NEIL GIBSON: 1%?

00:13:23.810 --> 00:13:25.850
No, it's 8%.

00:13:25.850 --> 00:13:27.761
What about vision?

00:13:27.761 --> 00:13:29.027
AUDIENCE: 30%.

00:13:29.027 --> 00:13:30.110
NEIL GIBSON: There you go.

00:13:30.110 --> 00:13:30.610
Well done.

00:13:30.610 --> 00:13:33.260
It is 30%.

00:13:33.260 --> 00:13:36.470
That's 10 times as
many as hearing.

00:13:36.470 --> 00:13:38.720
Vision dominates
the other senses.

00:13:38.720 --> 00:13:41.099
Even your retina itself is
an outcrop of the brain.

00:13:41.099 --> 00:13:43.640
It's the only part of the brain
that's not inside the cortex.

00:13:47.600 --> 00:13:48.560
So what?

00:13:48.560 --> 00:13:49.950
Why does that matter?

00:13:49.950 --> 00:13:52.740
Well, vision is so easy, it's
so quick to understand things.

00:13:52.740 --> 00:13:54.569
I'm going to show you
now four pictures,

00:13:54.569 --> 00:13:56.110
and in a fraction
of a second, you're

00:13:56.110 --> 00:13:58.520
going to get two or three
meanings from each picture

00:13:58.520 --> 00:14:00.470
without any effort.

00:14:00.470 --> 00:14:01.158
You ready?

00:14:03.850 --> 00:14:05.770
All right, done.

00:14:05.770 --> 00:14:08.840
Instantly all of you saw that
this is a toothbrush holder.

00:14:08.840 --> 00:14:09.710
That's a cloud.

00:14:09.710 --> 00:14:10.270
That's a bag.

00:14:10.270 --> 00:14:11.200
That's a sink.

00:14:11.200 --> 00:14:13.590
You also saw that's a
smiley face on these three.

00:14:13.590 --> 00:14:14.760
Maybe that's a Shopped one.

00:14:14.760 --> 00:14:17.140
And that's a human body.

00:14:17.140 --> 00:14:19.436
And if you want a bit more
detail, this is joyous.

00:14:19.436 --> 00:14:20.560
This one looks almost smug.

00:14:20.560 --> 00:14:22.210
And that one looks shocked.

00:14:22.210 --> 00:14:26.467
And that is not a euphoric
movement of that character,

00:14:26.467 --> 00:14:28.300
as it were, because
it's like it's stressed.

00:14:28.300 --> 00:14:29.091
It's under tension.

00:14:29.091 --> 00:14:30.416
Something's going on there.

00:14:30.416 --> 00:14:31.832
You can get those
meanings from it

00:14:31.832 --> 00:14:33.900
so quickly without any effort.

00:14:33.900 --> 00:14:37.080
And that's what I love
about how easy comics are--

00:14:37.080 --> 00:14:38.640
your understanding.

00:14:38.640 --> 00:14:40.360
You can instantly make
sense of pictures.

00:14:40.360 --> 00:14:42.169
And to give you another
example of this,

00:14:42.169 --> 00:14:43.960
I'm going to show you
just this panel here.

00:14:43.960 --> 00:14:45.710
Special bonus points
if anyone can tell me

00:14:45.710 --> 00:14:47.290
what comic this is from.

00:14:47.290 --> 00:14:51.730
But can someone tell me what
is going on in this panel?

00:14:51.730 --> 00:14:53.834
What do they see happening?

00:14:53.834 --> 00:14:54.710
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:14:54.710 --> 00:14:55.918
NEIL GIBSON: Fantastic, yeah.

00:14:55.918 --> 00:14:57.687
Perhaps that's a
padded room over there.

00:14:57.687 --> 00:15:00.020
Wherever they are, you can
tell it's been there a while.

00:15:00.020 --> 00:15:01.145
There's cracks in the wall.

00:15:01.145 --> 00:15:02.810
It's not a new location.

00:15:02.810 --> 00:15:05.200
To me, perhaps this is a
security guard by this cable

00:15:05.200 --> 00:15:06.890
here.

00:15:06.890 --> 00:15:08.650
What's interesting
to me is, I don't

00:15:08.650 --> 00:15:09.941
know if this is male or female.

00:15:09.941 --> 00:15:13.020
It's androgynous and
hair that's distinctive.

00:15:13.020 --> 00:15:15.460
To have the strength to break
someone's neck like that

00:15:15.460 --> 00:15:17.545
is extraordinary, but
it's not very muscly.

00:15:17.545 --> 00:15:19.125
There's Something unusual there.

00:15:19.125 --> 00:15:21.940
And this person seems totally
uninterested in this as well.

00:15:21.940 --> 00:15:23.620
There's no emotion on the face.

00:15:23.620 --> 00:15:25.900
And even these three
lines here implies hat

00:15:25.900 --> 00:15:27.592
this person is
distracted elsewhere.

00:15:27.592 --> 00:15:29.800
The girl is almost an
afterthought to this character.

00:15:29.800 --> 00:15:31.650
Even her dialogue is cut off.

00:15:31.650 --> 00:15:33.790
And the artist has changed
the angle of the panel

00:15:33.790 --> 00:15:36.220
to make it look more intense.

00:15:36.220 --> 00:15:37.110
This is all stuff--

00:15:37.110 --> 00:15:39.318
I don't even know what's
actually happening in there.

00:15:39.318 --> 00:15:41.410
This is what you can
pick up from the picture.

00:15:41.410 --> 00:15:42.400
And the reason I
mention all this

00:15:42.400 --> 00:15:44.066
is because a picture's
a thousand words.

00:15:44.066 --> 00:15:46.840
Communication through pictures
is incredibly efficient.

00:15:46.840 --> 00:15:48.429
If you choose the
time to look at it,

00:15:48.429 --> 00:15:50.720
because you can spend as much
time on this as you want,

00:15:50.720 --> 00:15:53.011
you can just look at it, go,
"oh, it's killed someone,"

00:15:53.011 --> 00:15:54.680
and you move on
to the next panel.

00:15:54.680 --> 00:15:57.570
It's your choice.

00:15:57.570 --> 00:16:00.150
Another advantage, though,
apart from the ease of vision,

00:16:00.150 --> 00:16:01.080
is memory retention.

00:16:01.080 --> 00:16:03.121
And this is where it gets
very interesting to me.

00:16:06.960 --> 00:16:08.587
Have you ever been
reading a book

00:16:08.587 --> 00:16:10.920
and you put it down for a day
or two, and you come back,

00:16:10.920 --> 00:16:12.670
and you you've lost
your page in the book?

00:16:12.670 --> 00:16:14.490
And you wonder,
where am I in this?

00:16:14.490 --> 00:16:15.540
And you flick through--

00:16:15.540 --> 00:16:17.440
have I read this
before, this bit or not?

00:16:17.440 --> 00:16:18.190
Yeah, some people.

00:16:18.190 --> 00:16:18.720
Yeah.

00:16:18.720 --> 00:16:20.178
What's more common,
you're actually

00:16:20.178 --> 00:16:22.620
reading a page of text, and
suddenly you realize, oh, I

00:16:22.620 --> 00:16:24.327
haven't taken any of this in.

00:16:24.327 --> 00:16:25.910
And you have to go
back and reread it.

00:16:25.910 --> 00:16:28.290
Everyone's experienced
that, right?

00:16:28.290 --> 00:16:31.950
With comics, both of these
happen a lot less frequency.

00:16:31.950 --> 00:16:33.480
First of all, for
the picture, it's

00:16:33.480 --> 00:16:36.840
because visual recall is
so much higher for images

00:16:36.840 --> 00:16:38.280
than it is for text.

00:16:38.280 --> 00:16:39.660
And they do studies--

00:16:39.660 --> 00:16:42.660
they've done studies on
babies and monkeys, babies

00:16:42.660 --> 00:16:44.990
with images of people.

00:16:44.990 --> 00:16:47.130
And if they keep showing
new people, new faces--

00:16:47.130 --> 00:16:48.897
and it can be same
with lemurs as well--

00:16:48.897 --> 00:16:51.480
humans can't really distinguish
between different lemurs, even

00:16:51.480 --> 00:16:53.646
humans who have worked with
them their entire lives.

00:16:53.646 --> 00:16:57.870
So a baby, way the
brain works, if it's

00:16:57.870 --> 00:16:59.626
a different image,
a different picture,

00:16:59.626 --> 00:17:00.750
it'll hold their attention.

00:17:00.750 --> 00:17:02.708
Show the same one twice,
and they'll look away.

00:17:02.708 --> 00:17:03.903
They've lost interest.

00:17:03.903 --> 00:17:05.819
Whereas with monkeys,
they've done experiments

00:17:05.819 --> 00:17:08.530
with the lever, and
they'll show photographs.

00:17:08.530 --> 00:17:10.140
If they've seen the
photograph before

00:17:10.140 --> 00:17:12.780
and they mark it as seen,
they get a banana pellet.

00:17:12.780 --> 00:17:15.780
If they haven't seen it before,
they'll mark the other way.

00:17:15.780 --> 00:17:18.270
And monkeys show
incredible memory retention

00:17:18.270 --> 00:17:19.631
for visual images.

00:17:19.631 --> 00:17:21.839
They can show them the
picture once three months ago,

00:17:21.839 --> 00:17:23.380
and they'll remember
they've seen it.

00:17:25.630 --> 00:17:29.650
As for not taking in a page,
again, your comprehension

00:17:29.650 --> 00:17:32.320
is usually much
higher with comics

00:17:32.320 --> 00:17:33.689
than it is with just text.

00:17:33.689 --> 00:17:35.480
You don't normally go
back and say, well, I

00:17:35.480 --> 00:17:36.896
haven't taken this
in, because you

00:17:36.896 --> 00:17:38.950
understand from the
pictures what's happening.

00:17:38.950 --> 00:17:43.390
Now, I do say "usually"
here, because just like there

00:17:43.390 --> 00:17:45.490
are some awful books,
there are some awful TV,

00:17:45.490 --> 00:17:47.110
there's some awful
music out there,

00:17:47.110 --> 00:17:49.040
there are some awful comics.

00:17:49.040 --> 00:17:49.780
Right?

00:17:49.780 --> 00:17:50.830
I do love the medium,
but it doesn't

00:17:50.830 --> 00:17:51.996
mean I love all the content.

00:17:54.620 --> 00:17:57.380
Now, combining the
recall aspect of this,

00:17:57.380 --> 00:17:59.630
that you can remember
it, and the comprehension

00:17:59.630 --> 00:18:02.424
gives you an advantage.

00:18:02.424 --> 00:18:04.840
And in neurology, this is
called the pictorial superiority

00:18:04.840 --> 00:18:05.870
effect.

00:18:05.870 --> 00:18:09.160
And Alex Lundry has done some
extensive research on this.

00:18:09.160 --> 00:18:10.760
If you present
information orally,

00:18:10.760 --> 00:18:12.490
like if I gave you
this talk without any

00:18:12.490 --> 00:18:17.380
of these pictures, just hearing
it as opposed to seeing it,

00:18:17.380 --> 00:18:22.000
72 hours after you hear
something, typically recall is,

00:18:22.000 --> 00:18:26.290
according to Alex Lundry,
10% if you just hear it.

00:18:26.290 --> 00:18:31.330
Whereas if you add pictures,
recall soars to 65%.

00:18:31.330 --> 00:18:34.060
Now, that to me
is extraordinary.

00:18:34.060 --> 00:18:37.120
Over six times as effective
recall when you add pictures

00:18:37.120 --> 00:18:39.320
to what you're saying.

00:18:39.320 --> 00:18:41.660
We are hard-wired to
find visualization more

00:18:41.660 --> 00:18:44.600
compelling than a spreadsheet.

00:18:44.600 --> 00:18:47.970
So look at this data here,
and please tell me which

00:18:47.970 --> 00:18:50.080
product or region is different.

00:18:50.080 --> 00:18:52.500
Region 3, absolutely.

00:18:52.500 --> 00:18:54.080
Showing this, here
you can clearly

00:18:54.080 --> 00:18:56.717
see that these have all gone
up but [? T ?] has gone down,

00:18:56.717 --> 00:18:58.800
whereas if you do this
graphically, red's gone up.

00:18:58.800 --> 00:19:00.530
The other two are trending down.

00:19:00.530 --> 00:19:05.120
Now, it shouldn't be news to
you that understanding this

00:19:05.120 --> 00:19:06.980
is easier than this, right?

00:19:06.980 --> 00:19:09.590
Now, there's science
behind why it's the case,

00:19:09.590 --> 00:19:11.720
but that's intuitive.

00:19:11.720 --> 00:19:13.940
What's interesting
is that if you're

00:19:13.940 --> 00:19:15.860
trying to make a point
in the presentation,

00:19:15.860 --> 00:19:17.510
not only is this
easier to understand,

00:19:17.510 --> 00:19:20.190
but people will remember
it more afterwards.

00:19:20.190 --> 00:19:21.590
And that's why you're giving
the talk in the first place,

00:19:21.590 --> 00:19:23.298
because you want it
to make a difference.

00:19:27.074 --> 00:19:28.592
So how can comics
actually help you?

00:19:28.592 --> 00:19:30.050
And I've gone
through and explained

00:19:30.050 --> 00:19:32.760
the advantages of the medium.

00:19:32.760 --> 00:19:34.760
Well, I used to work as
a management consultant.

00:19:34.760 --> 00:19:37.400
And I was on a project
in [? Amman ?] once.

00:19:37.400 --> 00:19:41.220
And this company was
building roads and bridges,

00:19:41.220 --> 00:19:42.720
and they had a
problem, because they

00:19:42.720 --> 00:19:45.890
had a production department
and a maintenance department.

00:19:45.890 --> 00:19:47.557
And the production
department, their job

00:19:47.557 --> 00:19:49.515
was to build, build,
build as fast as possible.

00:19:49.515 --> 00:19:50.890
They had deadlines to meet.

00:19:50.890 --> 00:19:52.556
Whereas the maintenance
department's job

00:19:52.556 --> 00:19:54.710
was to keep the equipment
maintained properly

00:19:54.710 --> 00:19:56.137
and avoid downtime.

00:19:56.137 --> 00:19:58.220
But they were experiencing
huge levels of downtime

00:19:58.220 --> 00:20:00.740
because the production guys
wouldn't release the equipment

00:20:00.740 --> 00:20:02.240
for maintenance,
because they wanted

00:20:02.240 --> 00:20:04.700
to meet their targets, which
resulted in when it did

00:20:04.700 --> 00:20:06.590
fail, failing
catastrophically, and having

00:20:06.590 --> 00:20:08.450
to do expensive
rebuilds and have

00:20:08.450 --> 00:20:11.370
expensive hiring for
emergency equipment.

00:20:11.370 --> 00:20:15.367
So the cheap solution
was to use a comic.

00:20:15.367 --> 00:20:17.700
"It's time for preventive
maintenance on the equipment."

00:20:17.700 --> 00:20:18.200
"No time.

00:20:18.200 --> 00:20:18.990
We have to work."

00:20:18.990 --> 00:20:20.240
"It'll just take three hours."

00:20:20.240 --> 00:20:21.780
"Nope, sorry."

00:20:21.780 --> 00:20:23.010
"At least let us grease it."

00:20:23.010 --> 00:20:23.855
"No time."

00:20:23.855 --> 00:20:25.480
And of course it breaks.

00:20:25.480 --> 00:20:26.910
"How much time to repair it?"

00:20:26.910 --> 00:20:27.510
"Oh, not long.

00:20:27.510 --> 00:20:29.700
Just three weeks."

