took me about 15 minutes,
most of it processing power

00:31:15.890 --> 00:31:16.930
for Prisma.

00:31:16.930 --> 00:31:19.640
15 minutes to the whole thing.

00:31:19.640 --> 00:31:21.980
If you want to get an
important message across,

00:31:21.980 --> 00:31:24.440
is it worth spending 15
minutes doing something

00:31:24.440 --> 00:31:28.397
that will engage people and
that they will remember?

00:31:28.397 --> 00:31:28.980
I think it is.

00:31:32.930 --> 00:31:36.264
So I'm just going back
to the presentation.

00:31:39.110 --> 00:31:43.944
And it's not just for studying
and for memory or for work.

00:31:43.944 --> 00:31:45.860
This is something we did
with a charity called

00:31:45.860 --> 00:31:49.850
Check One Two because it was
in conjunction with Stephen Fry

00:31:49.850 --> 00:31:53.720
and [? Anton Deck. ?] It's
about testicular cancer.

00:31:53.720 --> 00:31:55.400
Breast cancer has had
massive reductions

00:31:55.400 --> 00:31:57.730
in this country due to proper
screening and awareness,

00:31:57.730 --> 00:32:00.350
but testicular cancer has
stayed pretty much level.

00:32:00.350 --> 00:32:01.799
Men don't check themselves.

00:32:01.799 --> 00:32:03.590
So we made a comic
which was actually aimed

00:32:03.590 --> 00:32:07.670
at women to show men in
their lives, made it funny,

00:32:07.670 --> 00:32:10.760
having a little feel
there, testing himself.

00:32:10.760 --> 00:32:14.450
And this was just to get
people to check themselves.

00:32:14.450 --> 00:32:15.897
I think it's a
worthwhile message,

00:32:15.897 --> 00:32:17.230
and apparently it was effective.

00:32:17.230 --> 00:32:18.521
They used it in their campaign.

00:32:21.860 --> 00:32:24.380
So going back to why people
stopped reading comics

00:32:24.380 --> 00:32:28.390
at the end-- this is just
a parting message on this.

00:32:28.390 --> 00:32:30.412
People do stop
reading comics mostly

00:32:30.412 --> 00:32:32.620
because they don't evolve
the content they're taking.

00:32:32.620 --> 00:32:34.840
But there is so much
content out there

00:32:34.840 --> 00:32:36.460
which will suit
almost anyone's taste.

00:32:36.460 --> 00:32:38.410
I genuinely believe that.

00:32:38.410 --> 00:32:40.780
And you can read it
for many reasons.

00:32:40.780 --> 00:32:42.730
You can read it just
because you like stories,

00:32:42.730 --> 00:32:44.230
or because you like
fantasy stories,

00:32:44.230 --> 00:32:45.480
or you like superhero stories.

00:32:45.480 --> 00:32:46.542
Whatever you like.

00:32:46.542 --> 00:32:48.250
But let's say you like
historical comics.

00:32:48.250 --> 00:32:50.208
A lot of people ask me
if I could recommend one

00:32:50.208 --> 00:32:52.330
for comic for them,
what shall I recommend?

00:32:52.330 --> 00:32:55.090
My honest answer is, well,
if you're reading it just

00:32:55.090 --> 00:32:56.800
for fun and
enjoyment of reading,

00:32:56.800 --> 00:33:00.569
what content do you enjoy
film-wise or book-wise?

00:33:00.569 --> 00:33:02.110
So if someone says
they like history,

00:33:02.110 --> 00:33:04.270
well, I recommend "Maus."

00:33:04.270 --> 00:33:06.499
Anyone read this?

00:33:06.499 --> 00:33:07.540
Two people, three people.

00:33:07.540 --> 00:33:08.140
Good.

00:33:08.140 --> 00:33:10.060
So this is a fantastic comic.

00:33:10.060 --> 00:33:12.415
This is the first comic
to win a Pulitzer Prize.

00:33:12.415 --> 00:33:14.290
And this is set in the
'80s and in the run-up

00:33:14.290 --> 00:33:15.360
to the Second World War.

00:33:15.360 --> 00:33:17.110
And it's about this
guy who doesn't really

00:33:17.110 --> 00:33:18.310
get on with his father.

00:33:18.310 --> 00:33:21.070
He's a horrible man, but he
has incredible respect for him

00:33:21.070 --> 00:33:23.200
because he survived Auschwitz.

00:33:23.200 --> 00:33:25.510
And it makes you laugh,
and it makes you cry,

00:33:25.510 --> 00:33:27.850
and it educates you so much
of what actually happened.

00:33:27.850 --> 00:33:30.342
It's fascinating.

00:33:30.342 --> 00:33:32.050
Or let's say you want
to learn something.

00:33:32.050 --> 00:33:33.657
I studied engineering
at university,

00:33:33.657 --> 00:33:34.990
and my roommate studied physics.

00:33:34.990 --> 00:33:38.920
And he had this book called
"Introducing Einstein," which,

00:33:38.920 --> 00:33:41.290
because I read that, I know
the theory of relativity

00:33:41.290 --> 00:33:44.694
and I can explain it anyone,
which I think is fantastic.

00:33:44.694 --> 00:33:47.110
I doubt I would have gone and
picked up a textbook to read

00:33:47.110 --> 00:33:48.020
about the theory of relativity.

00:33:48.020 --> 00:33:51.040
But because it was in comic book
format and funny and well told,

00:33:51.040 --> 00:33:52.690
I definitely did.

00:33:52.690 --> 00:33:55.030
On the back of this,
though, as a warning,

00:33:55.030 --> 00:33:57.440
I read "Introducing
Chaos Theory,"

00:33:57.440 --> 00:33:58.690
and that was terribly written.

00:33:58.690 --> 00:34:00.740
I don't understand any of that.

00:34:00.740 --> 00:34:04.930
So if someone could explain that
to me later, that'd be great.

00:34:04.930 --> 00:34:05.687
Or about travel.

00:34:05.687 --> 00:34:07.270
If someone likes
travel, this is a guy

00:34:07.270 --> 00:34:09.460
who spent time in North Korea.

00:34:09.460 --> 00:34:13.750
And just how bizarre
the life style is there.

00:34:13.750 --> 00:34:17.620
Every public room
has photographs

00:34:17.620 --> 00:34:20.050
with frames at an angle, so
it's looking down at you,

00:34:20.050 --> 00:34:22.969
of the family.

00:34:22.969 --> 00:34:24.429
Or you can learn
about the economy

00:34:24.429 --> 00:34:26.989
or the Arab-Israeli Conflict.

00:34:26.989 --> 00:34:30.100
Or even if you're not
reading it for fun

00:34:30.100 --> 00:34:33.197
but for social interactions,
I have a Japanese friend.

00:34:33.197 --> 00:34:34.280
And this is amazing to me.

00:34:34.280 --> 00:34:36.400
I didn't even know this.

00:34:36.400 --> 00:34:39.130
She read a bunch of manga
when she moved to the UK

00:34:39.130 --> 00:34:41.409
on Shakespeare and classic
English literature,

00:34:41.409 --> 00:34:43.620
like "Pride and Prejudice,"
so that in dinner parties

00:34:43.620 --> 00:34:45.190
or in casual
conversation she could

00:34:45.190 --> 00:34:47.199
have a meaningful discussion
about these things

00:34:47.199 --> 00:34:50.460
without having to spend the time
of reading all these classics.

00:34:50.460 --> 00:34:52.080
Now, if they're
great classics, you

00:34:52.080 --> 00:34:52.810
might want to read
them yourselves

00:34:52.810 --> 00:34:54.280
for the enjoyment of it,
but if you're doing it

00:34:54.280 --> 00:34:56.710
for a different objective,
whatever your end result is,

00:34:56.710 --> 00:34:58.001
that's a great way of doing it.

00:34:58.001 --> 00:35:00.190
Again, because
it's quick to read,

00:35:00.190 --> 00:35:04.500
and you'll remember
it for conversations.

00:35:04.500 --> 00:35:06.750
So I think this
is my final slide.

00:35:06.750 --> 00:35:10.430
Are there any bad examples
of companies using comics?

00:35:10.430 --> 00:35:12.860
Yes, and I think
the biggest culprit

00:35:12.860 --> 00:35:17.720
worldwide has to be IKEA.

00:35:17.720 --> 00:35:18.920
This is awful.

00:35:18.920 --> 00:35:20.660
I mean, even the
structure of it.

00:35:20.660 --> 00:35:22.430
Books are the shape
they are for a reason.

00:35:22.430 --> 00:35:24.596
Over thousands of years,
there's science behind that

00:35:24.596 --> 00:35:26.359
as well, why humans
like that shape.

00:35:26.359 --> 00:35:28.400
You have to go all the
way across here before you

00:35:28.400 --> 00:35:29.544
find the first panel.

00:35:29.544 --> 00:35:31.210
If someone reads a
comic and people say,

00:35:31.210 --> 00:35:33.350
"oh, I don't know which
panels to read next,"

00:35:33.350 --> 00:35:35.300
that means the creators
have failed you.

00:35:35.300 --> 00:35:37.740
Because it should be easy,
the way the flow is done.

00:35:37.740 --> 00:35:40.825
They've had to put
numbers in this.

00:35:40.825 --> 00:35:44.530
And the journeys one will read
through this is there to there,

00:35:44.530 --> 00:35:48.020
to there, then it goes all
way over there, then down up.

00:35:48.020 --> 00:35:50.114
It's terrible.

00:35:50.114 --> 00:35:54.185
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE] pay
someone to do it for you.

00:35:54.185 --> 00:35:56.870
NEIL GIBSON: Well, my
feedback on this is,

00:35:56.870 --> 00:35:59.550
actually, has anyone ever
actually made something

00:35:59.550 --> 00:36:03.060
from IKEA and made a mistake?

00:36:03.060 --> 00:36:05.000
Yeah, you've never
made a mistake?

00:36:05.000 --> 00:36:06.140
Not once?

00:36:06.140 --> 00:36:08.320
AUDIENCE: I plan it out.

00:36:08.320 --> 00:36:10.070
NEIL GIBSON: Classic
Google employee here.

00:36:10.070 --> 00:36:10.730
Well done, sir.

00:36:10.730 --> 00:36:11.580
Well done.

00:36:11.580 --> 00:36:12.040
AUDIENCE: I get my
pencil and mark it.

00:36:12.040 --> 00:36:12.960
[INAUDIBLE]

00:36:12.960 --> 00:36:14.210
NEIL GIBSON: OK, that's great.

00:36:14.210 --> 00:36:15.584
I have a master's
in engineering,

00:36:15.584 --> 00:36:16.830
and I've made mistakes.

00:36:16.830 --> 00:36:17.500
OK?

00:36:17.500 --> 00:36:19.820
I think these are terrible
instructions, if I'm honest.

00:36:19.820 --> 00:36:21.230
And I don't think
anyone's made a mistake as

00:36:21.230 --> 00:36:23.510
bad as this woman, who's on the
floor in shame after what she

00:36:23.510 --> 00:36:24.100
did.

00:36:24.100 --> 00:36:27.590
I mean, that was
truly unforgivable.

00:36:27.590 --> 00:36:29.810
But if they gave
this to people who

00:36:29.810 --> 00:36:31.570
knew what they're doing
comic book people,

00:36:31.570 --> 00:36:33.650
they can make this so
much more engaging,

00:36:33.650 --> 00:36:36.270
and people wouldn't
make as many mistakes.

00:36:36.270 --> 00:36:39.017
And yes, IKEA do print this
on very thin, cheap paper,

00:36:39.017 --> 00:36:40.850
and they do it in as
few panels as possible,

00:36:40.850 --> 00:36:43.850
but I think adding an extra
two or three pages to this

00:36:43.850 --> 00:36:46.712
would make the experience so
much better for customers.

00:36:46.712 --> 00:36:48.920
They wouldn't have the dread
of having to assemble it

00:36:48.920 --> 00:36:51.050
or having to pay
other people about it.

00:36:51.050 --> 00:36:54.200
And they also maybe
even have a competition

00:36:54.200 --> 00:36:57.110
on Twitter about it, like
how was your experience?

00:36:57.110 --> 00:36:58.710
How many mistakes did you make?

00:36:58.710 --> 00:37:00.890
Turn it into a positive thing.

00:37:00.890 --> 00:37:03.350
If I was in IKEA, I'd definitely
be getting proper people

00:37:03.350 --> 00:37:04.420
to do this.

00:37:04.420 --> 00:37:07.270
And I actually think
in IKEA job interviews,

00:37:07.270 --> 00:37:10.860
they might want to
do this, and have

00:37:10.860 --> 00:37:12.840
their manual versus a
comic manual, someone

00:37:12.840 --> 00:37:14.900
who knows what they're doing.

00:37:14.900 --> 00:37:20.040
So in this talk, I've explain to
you about the public perception

00:37:20.040 --> 00:37:23.140
of comics, the advantages
of the medium, how

00:37:23.140 --> 00:37:26.580
it can be useful for you,
how to make your own comics.

00:37:26.580 --> 00:37:30.090
And I would really
love, if any of you

00:37:30.090 --> 00:37:33.210
have any questions after this,
to get in contact with me,

00:37:33.210 --> 00:37:36.400
because I want you guys
to use comics in some way.

00:37:36.400 --> 00:37:38.130
It could be helping
your children revise.

00:37:38.130 --> 00:37:41.940
It could be helping change the
culture of a different company.

00:37:41.940 --> 00:37:43.440
It could be a
significant problem

00:37:43.440 --> 00:37:45.356
that people are having
that you want to change

00:37:45.356 --> 00:37:46.440
or a marketing idea.

00:37:46.440 --> 00:37:48.180
Whatever it is,
I'd love to help,

00:37:48.180 --> 00:37:52.030
because I genuinely care about
the medium, and I think--

00:37:52.030 --> 00:37:54.750
actually, I know that if you
do use comments correctly,

00:37:54.750 --> 00:37:58.500
they really can help you, either
in your studies or your career.

00:37:58.500 --> 00:37:59.780
Hope you found it interesting.

00:37:59.780 --> 00:38:01.738
Thank for listening to me.

00:38:01.738 --> 00:38:04.058
[APPLAUSE]

00:38:05.412 --> 00:38:06.620
SPEAKER: Thank you very much.

00:38:06.620 --> 00:38:08.273
We do have time for questions.

00:38:14.190 --> 00:38:17.970
AUDIENCE: I just saw you
have described how anybody

00:38:17.970 --> 00:38:20.400
can draw using the images.

00:38:20.400 --> 00:38:23.060
Is that how you
have made this book?

00:38:23.060 --> 00:38:26.640
I mean, do you do
photo shoot-outs

00:38:26.640 --> 00:38:29.010
with actors or
something like that?

00:38:29.010 --> 00:38:31.410
How do you make a
big story out of it?

00:38:31.410 --> 00:38:33.410
NEIL GIBSON: I personally don't.

00:38:33.410 --> 00:38:35.040
That was just a quick
way of doing it,

00:38:35.040 --> 00:38:37.080
because when people
buy comics, they

00:38:37.080 --> 00:38:39.445
buy it for one of four reasons.

00:38:39.445 --> 00:38:41.070
And everyone has
their own preferences,

00:38:41.070 --> 00:38:42.750
but generally
speaking, the majority

00:38:42.750 --> 00:38:45.187
buy it for actually the
stories, then for the art,

00:38:45.187 --> 00:38:46.770
then for the coloring,
and some people

00:38:46.770 --> 00:38:48.930
buy just for the lettering,
if you can believe it.

00:38:48.930 --> 00:38:51.790
So a large market is
because of the artwork.

00:38:51.790 --> 00:38:53.790
So all the work we
do, it constantly

00:38:53.790 --> 00:38:55.794
gets better and better.

00:38:55.794 --> 00:38:57.960
So doing it using photos
is a cheat for some people,

00:38:57.960 --> 00:39:00.110
because they want
to actually see art.

00:39:00.110 --> 00:39:02.017
So that's why we don't.

00:39:02.017 --> 00:39:03.350
AUDIENCE: But you actually draw?

00:39:03.350 --> 00:39:03.710
NEIL GIBSON: Me?

00:39:03.710 --> 00:39:04.751
No, that requires talent.

00:39:04.751 --> 00:39:06.030
So no, I don't.

00:39:06.030 --> 00:39:07.835
No, I have a team of
artists I work with.

00:39:07.835 --> 00:39:08.668
AUDIENCE: Oh, I see.

00:39:11.789 --> 00:39:12.330
AUDIENCE: Hi.

00:39:12.330 --> 00:39:15.890
So one medium which
lots of people

00:39:15.890 --> 00:39:18.260
have got onto now with
all the forums and reddits

00:39:18.260 --> 00:39:19.460
and everything is memes.

00:39:19.460 --> 00:39:23.132
So that's kind of an
accessible comic creation.

00:39:23.132 --> 00:39:23.840
NEIL GIBSON: Yes.

00:39:23.840 --> 00:39:25.631
AUDIENCE: So what's
your thoughts on those?

00:39:30.230 --> 00:39:34.160
NEIL GIBSON: Comics are
actually sequential artwork,

00:39:34.160 --> 00:39:35.320
so it has to be time-based.

00:39:35.320 --> 00:39:38.260
Memes tend to be just one
picture, so that, to me,

00:39:38.260 --> 00:39:39.860
is a cartoon rather
than a comic.

00:39:39.860 --> 00:39:43.310
That's getting a bit analytical
about it, academic about it.

00:39:43.310 --> 00:39:44.715
But I think memes are great.

00:39:44.715 --> 00:39:45.840
Some of them are hilarious.

00:39:45.840 --> 00:39:46.839
Some of them are stupid.

00:39:46.839 --> 00:39:49.650
Some of them I don't
understand, frankly.

00:39:49.650 --> 00:39:52.750
But they can be very
effective, and the reason

00:39:52.750 --> 00:39:54.550
they are so popular
now is because people

00:39:54.550 --> 00:39:57.500
share them, because it speaks
to them, it gets a reaction.

00:39:57.500 --> 00:39:58.990
So the good ones are great.

00:39:58.990 --> 00:40:02.660
The bad ones, well, are
not shared for a reason.

00:40:02.660 --> 00:40:03.868
Is that a fair enough answer?

00:40:09.725 --> 00:40:11.100
Oh, by the way,
the best question

00:40:11.100 --> 00:40:14.095
gets a copy of my
brand-new book.

00:40:14.095 --> 00:40:16.470
This won't be available in
stores till I think next year.

00:40:16.470 --> 00:40:17.860
So the best question gets this.

00:40:17.860 --> 00:40:19.340
That's an incentive for you.

00:40:19.340 --> 00:40:21.515
AUDIENCE: That's
a lot of pressure.

00:40:21.515 --> 00:40:23.245
Yeah, I wanted to
ask if you have used

00:40:23.245 --> 00:40:24.960
a comic for your personal use?

00:40:24.960 --> 00:40:28.620
Not for careers or drawing
a comic for other companies.

00:40:28.620 --> 00:40:31.640
Have you created your own
comic for your personal use,

00:40:31.640 --> 00:40:33.500
like to educate your
kids or whatever?

00:40:37.650 --> 00:40:43.360
NEIL GIBSON: I did,
and it backfired on me.

00:40:43.360 --> 00:40:45.870
So I made this.

00:40:45.870 --> 00:40:49.100
This is cool "World
of Chub Chub."

00:40:49.100 --> 00:40:50.839
And this is true
stories of me as a kid.

00:40:50.839 --> 00:40:52.380
I mean, these are
stories my mum used

00:40:52.380 --> 00:40:55.980
to like telling everyone of what
I did, of what a bad kid I was,

00:40:55.980 --> 00:40:56.880
and how funny it was.

00:40:56.880 --> 00:40:57.720
It's funny now.

00:40:57.720 --> 00:40:59.170
It wasn't funny at the time.

00:40:59.170 --> 00:41:02.310
So I made this comic as a
gift to her for her birthday,

00:41:02.310 --> 00:41:04.110
and she found it so
funny she shared it

00:41:04.110 --> 00:41:06.540
with her friends, which
was not my intention.

00:41:06.540 --> 00:41:09.540
And then they all said, "Neil,
you have to publish this."

00:41:09.540 --> 00:41:10.770
"No, this is private.

00:41:10.770 --> 00:41:12.150
This is--" But no, they made me.

00:41:12.150 --> 00:41:12.900
She made me do it.

00:41:12.900 --> 00:41:15.180
So now everyone knows
what a bad kid I was.

00:41:15.180 --> 00:41:19.772
So I did it for my own
personal reasons, yes, but ah,

00:41:19.772 --> 00:41:21.230
I did it for
educational purposes--

00:41:21.230 --> 00:41:24.330
So for educational purposes,
I did it as well for one guy.

00:41:24.330 --> 00:41:26.250
Because he had
difficulty understanding

00:41:26.250 --> 00:41:30.090
the difference between
"affect" and "effect," right?

00:41:30.090 --> 00:41:31.690
And he was a writer.

00:41:31.690 --> 00:41:35.910
So I drew an image
of special effects,

00:41:35.910 --> 00:41:38.710
and the special effects
blew out in a big E shape.

00:41:38.710 --> 00:41:39.300
OK.

00:41:39.300 --> 00:41:41.008
And there was someone
else who went "Ah!"

00:41:41.008 --> 00:41:43.110
He was hit by it, and
he was shouting "Ah."

00:41:43.110 --> 00:41:48.270
And his body shape
was like an A.

00:41:48.270 --> 00:41:50.570
The special effects affect him.

00:41:50.570 --> 00:41:53.432
So that way, he's not
going to forget it.

00:41:53.432 --> 00:41:54.810
AUDIENCE: Was it effective?

00:41:54.810 --> 00:41:58.910
NEIL GIBSON: It was
effective, not affective, yes.

00:41:58.910 --> 00:41:59.880
Question?

