Yeah.

00:42:07.525 --> 00:42:09.150
AUDIENCE: What comics
do you personally

00:42:09.150 --> 00:42:11.570
enjoy reading for fun?

00:42:11.570 --> 00:42:13.070
NEIL GIBSON: I read
a lot of comics.

00:42:13.070 --> 00:42:15.410
I have a massive
library at home.

00:42:15.410 --> 00:42:19.940
Unfortunately, the comic
book world isn't that big.

00:42:19.940 --> 00:42:23.550
So I read all the
great stuff, I think.

00:42:23.550 --> 00:42:27.140
So my current
favorite right now is

00:42:27.140 --> 00:42:28.912
"Saga," which is the
biggest-selling comic

00:42:28.912 --> 00:42:29.870
in the world right now.

00:42:29.870 --> 00:42:31.245
It used to be "The
Walking Dead,"

00:42:31.245 --> 00:42:33.040
because it's overtaken them.

00:42:33.040 --> 00:42:38.680
But other than that, I'm
struggling to find good stuff.

00:42:38.680 --> 00:42:40.250
[INAUDIBLE] more
independent creators

00:42:40.250 --> 00:42:42.708
who aren't that professional,
but I meet them at comic cons

00:42:42.708 --> 00:42:44.030
and I buy their stuff.

00:42:44.030 --> 00:42:45.470
But if you have any
recommendations afterwards,

00:42:45.470 --> 00:42:47.180
I would love to hear
them, because I'm always

00:42:47.180 --> 00:42:48.221
looking for good content.

00:42:53.210 --> 00:42:55.300
AUDIENCE: Have
you had any issues

00:42:55.300 --> 00:42:59.030
with expressing something
that is somewhat

00:42:59.030 --> 00:43:04.130
like an abstract concept
in a way through comics?

00:43:04.130 --> 00:43:07.130
Like, for example,
there was the concept--

00:43:07.130 --> 00:43:10.370
there was the comic
about Einstein's--

00:43:13.820 --> 00:43:18.380
wouldn't that take some of the
value away that a wall of text

00:43:18.380 --> 00:43:22.730
would have in expressing
abstract concepts more easily?

00:43:22.730 --> 00:43:25.310
NEIL GIBSON: Ah, that's
a very good point.

00:43:25.310 --> 00:43:26.300
I've never had to--

00:43:26.300 --> 00:43:29.570
I've never personally had to
make very abstract concepts,

00:43:29.570 --> 00:43:33.760
because most of the stuff I
write or publish is fiction.

00:43:33.760 --> 00:43:36.052
Or it's very clear, the
message you want to get across.

00:43:36.052 --> 00:43:37.468
When it's something
very complic--

00:43:37.468 --> 00:43:39.420
Like, I've always thought
advanced mathematics

00:43:39.420 --> 00:43:40.890
and theoretical physicists
are the smartest

00:43:40.890 --> 00:43:42.720
people on the planet, because
the way their brains work,

00:43:42.720 --> 00:43:43.760
these concepts which--

00:43:43.760 --> 00:43:44.400
I get that.

00:43:44.400 --> 00:43:44.899
Oh, wait.

00:43:44.899 --> 00:43:46.090
No, I don't get it anymore.

00:43:46.090 --> 00:43:49.050
It's very difficult to
wrap your head around.

00:43:49.050 --> 00:43:51.650
I have not had to do it
myself, so "I don't know"

00:43:51.650 --> 00:43:52.980
is the answer for that.

00:43:52.980 --> 00:43:59.190
But I still think just from
when I was studying engineering,

00:43:59.190 --> 00:44:01.800
they bring in models
for you to look at,

00:44:01.800 --> 00:44:03.930
and rather than
just reading text,

00:44:03.930 --> 00:44:06.300
showing images always
is more effective.

00:44:06.300 --> 00:44:08.540
I still remember those
models years later.

00:44:08.540 --> 00:44:10.410
AUDIENCE: Yeah, but
I guess the problem

00:44:10.410 --> 00:44:13.320
is how to show them
so that you express

00:44:13.320 --> 00:44:17.735
more abstract concepts in a
way that is visually memorable.

00:44:17.735 --> 00:44:19.110
NEIL GIBSON: I
think you're going

00:44:19.110 --> 00:44:21.058
to have to give me an
example of something.

00:44:23.926 --> 00:44:29.700
AUDIENCE: Like if
you teach programming

00:44:29.700 --> 00:44:31.509
to someone for instance.

00:44:31.509 --> 00:44:32.550
NEIL GIBSON: Programming?

00:44:32.550 --> 00:44:33.304
AUDIENCE: Yes.

00:44:33.304 --> 00:44:33.970
NEIL GIBSON: OK.

00:44:38.400 --> 00:44:46.860
AUDIENCE: I don't see a way of
expressing that through comics

00:44:46.860 --> 00:44:50.950
without having a wall of
text in one of the comics,

00:44:50.950 --> 00:44:53.859
or just having
text with examples.

00:44:53.859 --> 00:44:55.400
NEIL GIBSON: Oh, I
see what you mean.

00:44:55.400 --> 00:44:56.040
OK, fine.

00:44:56.040 --> 00:44:56.946
Yes, fine.

00:44:56.946 --> 00:44:58.320
Well, for programming,
you'd have

00:44:58.320 --> 00:45:01.960
to have the text, because that's
what you're actually doing.

00:45:01.960 --> 00:45:03.079
But I'll tell you what.

00:45:03.079 --> 00:45:04.620
If you actually want
to discuss this,

00:45:04.620 --> 00:45:05.990
I can talk to you
afterwards, and we can

00:45:05.990 --> 00:45:06.970
go through a practical example.

00:45:06.970 --> 00:45:09.594
I'll see if I can actually help
you on that, because I actually

00:45:09.594 --> 00:45:11.130
would love to see if I could.

00:45:11.130 --> 00:45:13.480
AUDIENCE: Have you seen Scratch?

00:45:13.480 --> 00:45:14.305
NEIL GIBSON: Nope.

00:45:14.305 --> 00:45:14.840
AUDIENCE: Scratch is a kind
of a graphical programming

00:45:14.840 --> 00:45:16.319
environment.

00:45:16.319 --> 00:45:17.599
NEIL GIBSON: Ah.

00:45:17.599 --> 00:45:19.140
AUDIENCE: Yeah, but
that's different.

00:45:19.140 --> 00:45:24.300
I was just thinking
if we could express

00:45:24.300 --> 00:45:27.060
textbook sort of
subjects into comics

00:45:27.060 --> 00:45:34.752
and whether this would be
a limitation of comics.

00:45:34.752 --> 00:45:35.835
NEIL GIBSON: I don't know.

00:45:35.835 --> 00:45:38.168
I'll talk to you afterward
about it, but what I will say

00:45:38.168 --> 00:45:41.420
is I remember when I was
young, science textbooks, they

00:45:41.420 --> 00:45:44.652
were very text-heavy and didn't
have many pictures, compared

00:45:44.652 --> 00:45:48.140
to by the time I got to just
before I started university,

00:45:48.140 --> 00:45:50.030
they were so much more
glossy with color,

00:45:50.030 --> 00:45:53.724
and they had a lot, maybe
five times as many diagrams

00:45:53.724 --> 00:45:55.640
as the ones that were
around when I was a kid,

00:45:55.640 --> 00:45:57.740
because they're effective.

00:45:57.740 --> 00:45:59.560
So I do think there
probably is a way,

00:45:59.560 --> 00:46:01.310
but I have to go into
the specifics of how

00:46:01.310 --> 00:46:02.090
to actually help you on this.

00:46:02.090 --> 00:46:03.450
I have to discuss afterwards.

00:46:03.450 --> 00:46:05.407
So no one fault me, OK?

00:46:05.407 --> 00:46:06.385
Good, OK.

00:46:14.710 --> 00:46:18.200
AUDIENCE: This is more
of a follow-up to that.

00:46:18.200 --> 00:46:21.490
So there are some comic
book textbooks that exist.

00:46:21.490 --> 00:46:23.620
So for example, "The
Manga Guide to Databases."

00:46:23.620 --> 00:46:28.890
There is a lot of text in it,
but giving it reasons to exist.

00:46:28.890 --> 00:46:30.640
Like, why do you care
about normalization?

00:46:30.640 --> 00:46:32.320
Well, you care about it
because otherwise you

00:46:32.320 --> 00:46:34.153
might be giving apples
to the Fairy Kingdom,

00:46:34.153 --> 00:46:36.270
and you shouldn't be doing that.

00:46:36.270 --> 00:46:38.770
So that can be helpful.

00:46:38.770 --> 00:46:41.290
And also you can
better express--

00:46:41.290 --> 00:46:42.400
so there's a book.

00:46:42.400 --> 00:46:43.390
It's not a comic book.

00:46:43.390 --> 00:46:48.130
It's a regular book
book called "If I Only

00:46:48.130 --> 00:46:51.140
Changed the Software, Why
is the Phone on Fire?"

00:46:51.140 --> 00:46:55.599
which is useful for teaching
process-related bits of coding,

00:46:55.599 --> 00:46:57.640
for example, that are
quite difficult to describe

00:46:57.640 --> 00:47:02.485
in a traditional
textbook format.

00:47:02.485 --> 00:47:04.960
So thought processes, how
stuff happens, and this

00:47:04.960 --> 00:47:07.040
is done with a
cast of characters

00:47:07.040 --> 00:47:09.990
as a kind of mystery
novel type thing.

00:47:09.990 --> 00:47:10.601
So.

00:47:10.601 --> 00:47:11.351
NEIL GIBSON: Cool.

00:47:16.835 --> 00:47:17.335
Yeah.

00:47:20.720 --> 00:47:23.190
AUDIENCE: What do you think
of digital comics or comics

00:47:23.190 --> 00:47:25.600
in a digital form?

00:47:25.600 --> 00:47:29.310
NEIL GIBSON: OK, so
that's a good question.

00:47:29.310 --> 00:47:32.910
I think you're the contender
for this one right now.

00:47:32.910 --> 00:47:35.010
I personally get enough--

00:47:35.010 --> 00:47:36.990
like you guys, probably
get enough screen time.

00:47:36.990 --> 00:47:38.542
So I personally prefer reading.

00:47:38.542 --> 00:47:40.750
I like touching the books
and reading it and flicking

00:47:40.750 --> 00:47:40.860
through.

00:47:40.860 --> 00:47:43.401
I like having a library where
I can see everything I've read.

00:47:43.401 --> 00:47:46.470
So I personally prefer print
massively to digital ones.

00:47:46.470 --> 00:47:49.170
However, I'm old, OK?

00:47:49.170 --> 00:47:51.002
Young people like
reading digital comics,

00:47:51.002 --> 00:47:51.960
and that is the future.

00:47:51.960 --> 00:47:53.940
Because with digital comics,
you can reach a mass market.

00:47:53.940 --> 00:47:55.950
You can get anyone in
the world instant access

00:47:55.950 --> 00:47:58.500
to your material, and you
can share it so much easier.

00:48:01.472 --> 00:48:03.430
The thing with digital
comics, though, as well,

00:48:03.430 --> 00:48:09.580
is what's interesting to
me is that right now people

00:48:09.580 --> 00:48:11.712
will go into Waterstones
or Barnes &amp; Noble,

00:48:11.712 --> 00:48:14.170
look at the books they want to
buy, and then on their phone

00:48:14.170 --> 00:48:18.250
buy it on Kindle as they're
walking out the shop.

00:48:18.250 --> 00:48:22.030
Digital sales of books
exceed print sales of books

00:48:22.030 --> 00:48:23.420
and they cannibalize it.

00:48:23.420 --> 00:48:25.320
That doesn't happen in comics.

00:48:25.320 --> 00:48:27.700
In comics, digital sales
increase print sales

00:48:27.700 --> 00:48:30.101
because people want to have
the physical copy as well.

00:48:30.101 --> 00:48:31.100
So I think that's great.

00:48:31.100 --> 00:48:33.350
I don't think comics are
going to go anywhere.

00:48:33.350 --> 00:48:34.540
The consumption does change.

00:48:34.540 --> 00:48:36.010
It used to be all
floppies, but now it's

00:48:36.010 --> 00:48:37.060
all moved to trade paperbacks.

00:48:37.060 --> 00:48:38.851
This is the big growth
area, because people

00:48:38.851 --> 00:48:40.900
like having a proper book.

00:48:40.900 --> 00:48:43.180
But digital comics
have their place.

00:48:43.180 --> 00:48:44.440
A lot of people love them.

00:48:44.440 --> 00:48:45.766
I personally like a book.

00:48:49.660 --> 00:48:51.880
AUDIENCE: Just as a
follow-on to that,

00:48:51.880 --> 00:48:55.090
I almost exclusively read
digital comics, the reason

00:48:55.090 --> 00:48:58.480
being, if I have a
comic book in my hand,

00:48:58.480 --> 00:49:00.850
I will want to read
the entire thing.

00:49:00.850 --> 00:49:02.470
And comic books
these days are too

00:49:02.470 --> 00:49:05.290
long to read the entire thing,
and it feels really jarring.

00:49:05.290 --> 00:49:07.300
I do the same with
actual novels as well.

00:49:07.300 --> 00:49:11.530
But episodic digital
comics are beneficial,

00:49:11.530 --> 00:49:13.765
because there's only
one new page every week.

00:49:13.765 --> 00:49:17.774
So you're limited in how
much you can binge read.

00:49:17.774 --> 00:49:19.190
NEIL GIBSON: I
like binge reading.

00:49:19.190 --> 00:49:20.440
I like binge watching Netflix.

00:49:20.440 --> 00:49:22.690
AUDIENCE: I do too, but I can't.

00:49:22.690 --> 00:49:25.640
NEIL GIBSON: That's
a fair enough point.

00:49:25.640 --> 00:49:27.885
Look, it's how you
want to consume it.

00:49:27.885 --> 00:49:30.790
That's all your choice.

00:49:30.790 --> 00:49:34.237
I personally do think
that when you binge read,

00:49:34.237 --> 00:49:36.070
you get more of the
creator's vision for it,

00:49:36.070 --> 00:49:37.236
because the story continues.

00:49:37.236 --> 00:49:40.364
You don't forget things as much.

00:49:40.364 --> 00:49:42.280
I'm quite looking forward
to "Game of Thrones"

00:49:42.280 --> 00:49:43.960
when it comes out
later this year,

00:49:43.960 --> 00:49:46.360
but I am probably going to
go back and try and find

00:49:46.360 --> 00:49:48.160
an online catch-up
in an hour where

00:49:48.160 --> 00:49:50.494
I can go through everything
that's happened in the past.

00:49:50.494 --> 00:49:52.285
Whereas, so if you're
reading it in one go,

00:49:52.285 --> 00:49:53.410
you don't need to do that.

00:49:53.410 --> 00:49:55.140
You can read it once.

00:49:55.140 --> 00:49:57.190
But it's individual taste.

00:50:00.540 --> 00:50:02.310
AUDIENCE: So I guess
a different form

00:50:02.310 --> 00:50:07.560
of digital comics, do you
have any experience with--

00:50:07.560 --> 00:50:10.320
particularly for the
industrial applications--

00:50:10.320 --> 00:50:12.330
interactive comics?

00:50:12.330 --> 00:50:15.750
NEIL GIBSON: Yes, I
have experienced them.

00:50:15.750 --> 00:50:18.210
I don't like them.

00:50:18.210 --> 00:50:21.732
Now, I think there's a
reason it hasn't taken off.

00:50:21.732 --> 00:50:23.940
It could be that there hasn't
been enough good enough

00:50:23.940 --> 00:50:28.890
content, but I think if
it's like a web comic, where

00:50:28.890 --> 00:50:31.055
it's just one button,
so you have the image

00:50:31.055 --> 00:50:33.450
and then you click the button
and something extra happens

00:50:33.450 --> 00:50:37.170
just there, that is interactive,
and that has its place.

00:50:37.170 --> 00:50:40.150
But it hasn't taken
off in the mainstream,

00:50:40.150 --> 00:50:42.940
because it's not really a comic.

00:50:42.940 --> 00:50:45.110
It's sort of a hybrid.

00:50:45.110 --> 00:50:48.280
And maybe there's some
great stuff out there,

00:50:48.280 --> 00:50:50.020
but I've yet to see
one where I go, wow,

00:50:50.020 --> 00:50:52.409
I really enjoyed this, whereas
there are dozens of comics

00:50:52.409 --> 00:50:54.950
which I recommend to people and
say, look, this is fantastic.

00:50:54.950 --> 00:50:56.950
I know you will enjoy it.

00:50:56.950 --> 00:50:58.744
AUDIENCE: OK.

00:50:58.744 --> 00:51:00.160
NEIL GIBSON: It's
my nemesis here.

00:51:03.860 --> 00:51:06.590
AUDIENCE: So just a thought
it's on industry comics.

00:51:06.590 --> 00:51:09.090
They're really good for
getting across a concept,

00:51:09.090 --> 00:51:11.370
getting people to
read the new concept,

00:51:11.370 --> 00:51:12.622
and getting information out.

00:51:12.622 --> 00:51:13.330
NEIL GIBSON: Yes.

00:51:13.330 --> 00:51:15.660
AUDIENCE: But they're
really bad for reference.

00:51:15.660 --> 00:51:18.390
So you always need
the text counterpart

00:51:18.390 --> 00:51:21.780
to be able to look things up,
because you can't look things

00:51:21.780 --> 00:51:25.132
up inside a visual novel.

00:51:25.132 --> 00:51:27.090
NEIL GIBSON: What do you
mean "look things up?"

00:51:27.090 --> 00:51:28.710
AUDIENCE: So something
has happened.

00:51:28.710 --> 00:51:30.420
You need to instantly
reference what

00:51:30.420 --> 00:51:32.670
to do to fix that situation.

00:51:32.670 --> 00:51:34.080
Basically, an index.

00:51:34.080 --> 00:51:36.775
How do you index
into a visual novel,

00:51:36.775 --> 00:51:38.400
where the information
could be anywhere

00:51:38.400 --> 00:51:39.930
on a page, anywhere in a book?

00:51:43.114 --> 00:51:44.780
NEIL GIBSON: Can you
give me an example?

00:51:44.780 --> 00:51:48.890
AUDIENCE: For instance, say one
of the databases is blurring up

00:51:48.890 --> 00:51:50.220
and there's an error.

00:51:50.220 --> 00:51:53.360
How do I find this in my
graphical novel information

00:51:53.360 --> 00:51:54.520
about how to fix errors?

00:51:54.520 --> 00:51:54.740
NEIL GIBSON: Right.

00:51:54.740 --> 00:51:56.220
Well, to me, then
that's a process flow.

00:51:56.220 --> 00:51:56.720
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

00:51:56.720 --> 00:51:57.590
NEIL GIBSON: So you
see the flowchart.

00:51:57.590 --> 00:51:59.010
You don't need a
graphic novel for that.

00:51:59.010 --> 00:51:59.635
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

00:51:59.635 --> 00:52:03.056
NEIL GIBSON: Graphic novels
are for telling a story.

00:52:03.056 --> 00:52:04.805
You knew that when you
asked the question.

00:52:04.805 --> 00:52:05.310
AUDIENCE: I'm just saying--

00:52:05.310 --> 00:52:06.420
NEIL GIBSON: You're my nemesis.

00:52:06.420 --> 00:52:08.586
I was going to give you
this comic, but not anymore.

00:52:11.642 --> 00:52:13.100
SPEAKER: I think
we can close here,

00:52:13.100 --> 00:52:16.782
so please join me in
thanking Neil Gibson.

00:52:16.782 --> 00:52:17.740
NEIL GIBSON: Thank you.

00:52:17.740 --> 00:52:18.940
Thank you, guys.

00:52:18.940 --> 00:52:21.690
[APPLAUSE]

